import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.dates as mdates

# Load the Excel file
file_path = r'PUT YOUR DIRECTORY'
xls = pd.ExcelFile(file_path)

# Load the worksheet
df = pd.read_excel(xls, sheet_name='Foglio1')

# Define column names manually for the 6 banks
banks = ["Credit Agricole", "BNP", "Intesa", "Unicredit", "BBVA", "Santander"]
columns_per_bank = ["Date", "Call Price", "Ivol", "ATM Strike", "Expiration"]

# Create a dictionary to store data for each bank
bank_data = {}

# Extract data for each bank
for i, bank in enumerate(banks):
    start_col = i * 5  # Each bank has 5 columns
    bank_df = df.iloc[1:, start_col:start_col + 5]  # Ignore the first row, which contains column names
    bank_df.columns = columns_per_bank  # Rename the columns
    bank_df = bank_df.dropna()  # Remove any empty rows
    bank_df["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(bank_df["Date"])  # Convert dates
    bank_df["Call Price"] = pd.to_numeric(bank_df["Call Price"], errors='coerce')  # Convert call prices
    bank_df["ATM Strike"] = pd.to_numeric(bank_df["ATM Strike"], errors='coerce')  # Convert strike prices
    bank_data[bank] = bank_df

# Create plots with a more readable style
plt.style.use("seaborn-whitegrid")  # Cleaner style

fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize=(15, 15), sharex=True, sharey=False)
axes = axes.flatten()

for i, (bank, data) in enumerate(bank_data.items()):
    ax = axes[i]
    ax.plot(data["Date"], data["Call Price"], label="Call Price", linestyle='dashed', color='red', linewidth=1.2)
    ax.plot(data["Date"], data["ATM Strike"], label="Strike Price", linestyle='dashdot', color='orange', linewidth=1.2)
    
    # Format x-axis
    ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.MonthLocator(interval=3))  # Show a date every 3 months
    ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%Y-%m'))  # Format as year-month
    ax.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)
    
    # Title and legend
    ax.set_title(f"Call Price and Strike Price Trend - {bank}", fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    ax.set_ylabel("Price", fontsize=10)
    ax.legend(fontsize=9, loc='upper right')

fig.suptitle("Call and Strike Price Trends of Banks", fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
fig.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.96], pad=6.0)  # More space between plots

plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the Excel file
file_path = r'PUT YOUR DIRECTORY'
xls = pd.ExcelFile(file_path)

# Load the data from the correct sheet
df = pd.read_excel(xls, sheet_name='Foglio1')

# Define new column names based on the file structure
df.columns = [
    "Date_Credit_Agricole", "Call_Price_Credit_Agricole", "Ivol_Credit_Agricole", "ATM_Strike_Credit_Agricole",
    "Expiration_Credit_Agricole", "Date_BNP", "Call_Price_BNP", "Ivol_BNP", "ATM_Strike_BNP", "Expiration_BNP",
    "Date_Intesa", "Call_Price_Intesa", "Ivol_Intesa", "ATM_Strike_Intesa", "Expiration_Intesa",
    "Date_UniCredit", "Call_Price_UniCredit", "Ivol_UniCredit", "ATM_Strike_UniCredit", "Expiration_UniCredit",
    "Date_BBVA", "Call_Price_BBVA", "Ivol_BBVA", "ATM_Strike_BBVA", "Expiration_BBVA",
    "Date_Santander", "Call_Price_Santander", "Ivol_Santander", "ATM_Strike_Santander", "Expiration_Santander"
]

# Remove the first row, which might be an additional header
df_cleaned = df.iloc[1:].copy()

# Select only the relevant columns for the plot
df_cleaned = df_cleaned[[
    "Date_Credit_Agricole", "Call_Price_Credit_Agricole", 
    "Date_BNP", "Call_Price_BNP", 
    "Date_Intesa", "Call_Price_Intesa", 
    "Date_UniCredit", "Call_Price_UniCredit", 
    "Date_BBVA", "Call_Price_BBVA", 
    "Date_Santander", "Call_Price_Santander"
]]

# Convert date columns to datetime format
date_columns = ["Date_Credit_Agricole", "Date_BNP", "Date_Intesa", "Date_UniCredit", "Date_BBVA", "Date_Santander"]
for col in date_columns:
    df_cleaned[col] = pd.to_datetime(df_cleaned[col], errors='coerce')

# Convert call option prices to numeric format
price_columns = ["Call_Price_Credit_Agricole", "Call_Price_BNP", "Call_Price_Intesa", 
                 "Call_Price_UniCredit", "Call_Price_BBVA", "Call_Price_Santander"]
for col in price_columns:
    df_cleaned[col] = pd.to_numeric(df_cleaned[col], errors='coerce')

# Create the plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(df_cleaned["Date_Credit_Agricole"], df_cleaned["Call_Price_Credit_Agricole"], label="Credit Agricole")
plt.plot(df_cleaned["Date_BNP"], df_cleaned["Call_Price_BNP"], label="BNP Paribas")
plt.plot(df_cleaned["Date_Intesa"], df_cleaned["Call_Price_Intesa"], label="Intesa Sanpaolo")
plt.plot(df_cleaned["Date_UniCredit"], df_cleaned["Call_Price_UniCredit"], label="UniCredit")
plt.plot(df_cleaned["Date_BBVA"], df_cleaned["Call_Price_BBVA"], label="BBVA")
plt.plot(df_cleaned["Date_Santander"], df_cleaned["Call_Price_Santander"], label="Santander")

# Format the plot
plt.xlabel("Date")
plt.ylabel("Call Price ()")
plt.title("Call Option Prices Over Time")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D
from scipy.interpolate import griddata

# Assuming df has already been loaded and cleaned

# Define column indices for each bank
bank_columns = {
    "Credit Agricole": [0, 1, 2, 3, 4],
    "BNP": [5, 6, 7, 8, 9],
    "ISP": [10, 11, 12, 13, 14],
    "UCG": [15, 16, 17, 18, 19],
    "SAN": [20, 21, 22, 23, 24],
    "BBVA": [25, 26, 27, 28, 29],
}

# Dictionary to store cleaned data for each bank
bank_data = {}

for bank, cols in bank_columns.items():
    try:
        df_bank = df.iloc[:, cols].copy()
        
        # Rename columns
        df_bank.columns = ["Date", "Call Price", "Ivol", "Strike", "Expiration"]
        
        # Convert data to the correct formats
        df_bank["Strike"] = pd.to_numeric(df_bank["Strike"], errors='coerce')
        df_bank["Ivol"] = pd.to_numeric(df_bank["Ivol"], errors='coerce')
        df_bank["Expiration"] = pd.to_datetime(df_bank["Expiration"], errors='coerce')

        # Remove rows with missing data
        df_bank = df_bank.dropna()

        # Save in the dictionary
        bank_data[bank] = df_bank

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error processing data for {bank}: {e}")

# Create implied volatility surfaces for each bank
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 15))

for i, (bank, df_bank) in enumerate(bank_data.items(), 1):
    ax = fig.add_subplot(2, 3, i, projection='3d')

    # Extract values
    strikes = df_bank["Strike"].values
    maturities = df_bank["Expiration"].values
    ivol = df_bank["Ivol"].values

    # Convert dates to days until expiration
    t0 = maturities.min()
    days_to_expiry = np.array([(t - t0) / np.timedelta64(1, 'D') for t in maturities], dtype=int)

    # Create a grid for interpolation
    strike_range = np.linspace(strikes.min(), strikes.max(), 50)
    time_range = np.linspace(days_to_expiry.min(), days_to_expiry.max(), 50)
    strike_grid, time_grid = np.meshgrid(strike_range, time_range)

    # Interpolate implied volatility
    ivol_grid = griddata((strikes, days_to_expiry), ivol, (strike_grid, time_grid), method='cubic')

    # Handle NaN values to avoid rendering issues
    ivol_grid = np.nan_to_num(ivol_grid, nan=0.0)

    # Plot the surface
    ax.plot_surface(strike_grid, time_grid, ivol_grid, cmap='viridis', edgecolor='none', alpha=0.8)

    # Plot a wireframe for better visibility
    ax.plot_wireframe(strike_grid, time_grid, ivol_grid, color='purple', alpha=0.5)

    # Axis labels
    ax.set_xlabel('Strike Price (K)')
    ax.set_ylabel('Time to Maturity (T)')
    ax.set_zlabel('Implied Volatility')
    ax.set_title(f'Implied Volatility Surface for {bank}')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

## Plotting market call option prices in 2023
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the Excel file
file_path = r'PUT YOUR DIRECTORY'

# Load data from the second sheet
df = pd.read_excel(file_path, sheet_name="FOGLIO 2")

# Clean the data
df.columns = ["Date", "Credit Agricole", "BNP", "Intesa", "Unicredit", "BBVA", "Santander"]
df = df.iloc[1:].reset_index(drop=True)  # Remove the repeated header row

# Convert the Date column to datetime format
df["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Date"])

# Convert price columns to numeric values
for col in df.columns[1:]:
    df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors='coerce')

# Create plots for each bank
for col in df.columns[1:]:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.plot(df["Date"], df[col], marker='o', linestyle='-')
    plt.xlabel("Date")
    plt.ylabel("Call Price")
    plt.title(f"Call Option Price Trend - {col}")
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from scipy.stats import norm
import os
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Black-Scholes function
def black_scholes(S, K, T, r, sigma, option_type="call"):
    d1 = (np.log(S / K) + (r + 0.5 * sigma**2) * T) / (sigma * np.sqrt(T))
    d2 = d1 - sigma * np.sqrt(T)

    if option_type == "call":
        return S * norm.cdf(d1) - K * np.exp(-r * T) * norm.cdf(d2)
    elif option_type == "put":
        return K * np.exp(-r * T) * norm.cdf(-d2) - S * norm.cdf(-d1)
    else:
        raise ValueError("Invalid option type. Use 'call' or 'put'.")

# Greeks calculation functions
def calculate_greeks(S, K, T, r, sigma, option_type="call"):
    d1 = (np.log(S / K) + (r + 0.5 * sigma**2) * T) / (sigma * np.sqrt(T))
    d2 = d1 - sigma * np.sqrt(T)

    delta = norm.cdf(d1) if option_type == "call" else -norm.cdf(-d1)
    gamma = norm.pdf(d1) / (S * sigma * np.sqrt(T))
    vega = S * norm.pdf(d1) * np.sqrt(T) / 100  # Expressed per 1% change in volatility
    theta = - (S * norm.pdf(d1) * sigma) / (2 * np.sqrt(T))
    if option_type == "call":
        theta -= r * K * np.exp(-r * T) * norm.cdf(d2)
    else:
        theta += r * K * np.exp(-r * T) * norm.cdf(-d2)
    theta /= 365  # Per day
    rho = K * T * np.exp(-r * T) * (norm.cdf(d2) if option_type == "call" else -norm.cdf(-d2)) / 100  # Per 1% change in rates

    return delta, gamma, vega, theta, rho

# Load the Excel file
file_path = r'PUT YOUR DIRECTORY'

# Load the second sheet from the Excel file
data = pd.ExcelFile(file_path)
df = data.parse(data.sheet_names[1])  # Load the second sheet

# Data cleaning
columns_mapping = {
    "Unnamed: 0": "Date",
    "ISP IM Equity": "ISP_Price",
    "UCG IM Equity": "UCG_Price",
    "SAN SM Equity": "SAN_Price",
    "BBVA SM Equity": "BBVA_Price",
    "ACA FP Equity": "ACA_Price",
    "BNP FP Equity": "BNP_Price",
    "EUDR1T Curncy": "RiskFreeRate"
}
df = df.rename(columns=columns_mapping)
df = df[~df["Date"].astype(str).str.contains("DATES", na=False)]
df["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Date"], errors='coerce')
df = df.dropna(subset=["Date", "RiskFreeRate"])
df.set_index("Date", inplace=True)

stocks = ["ISP_Price", "UCG_Price", "SAN_Price", "BBVA_Price", "ACA_Price", "BNP_Price"]
for stock in stocks:
    df_stock = df[[stock, "RiskFreeRate"]].dropna()
    quarterly_strike_prices = df_stock[stock].resample('Q').mean()
    print(f"\nQuarterly Average Prices (Strike Prices) for {stock}:")
    print(quarterly_strike_prices)

    # Calculate parameters for the Black-Scholes model
    current_price = df_stock[stock].iloc[-1]
    strike_price = quarterly_strike_prices.iloc[-1]
    time_to_maturity = 0.25  # One quarter in years
    risk_free_rate = df_stock["RiskFreeRate"].iloc[-1] / 100  # Convert to decimal form
    volatility = df_stock[stock].pct_change().std() * np.sqrt(252)  # Annualized volatility

    # Calculate option prices
    call_price = black_scholes(current_price, strike_price, time_to_maturity, risk_free_rate, volatility, option_type="call")
    put_price = black_scholes(current_price, strike_price, time_to_maturity, risk_free_rate, volatility, option_type="put")

    # Output the results
    print(f"Call Option Price for {stock}: {call_price:.2f}")
    print(f"Put Option Price for {stock}: {put_price:.2f}")

    # Create a plot of the price and quarterly strike prices
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

    # Plot Call Option Prices
    plt.plot(df_stock.index, [black_scholes(price, strike_price, time_to_maturity, risk_free_rate, volatility, option_type="call") for price in df_stock[stock]], 
             label=f'Call Price {stock}', color='green', linestyle='--')
    
    # Insert red vertical line
    plt.axvline(pd.Timestamp("2023-01-01"), color='red', linestyle='--', label="Starting date of our analysis")

    # Add title, labels, and legend
    plt.title(f'Call Price Trend for {stock} using BS Model')
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Price')
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)

    # Show the plot
    plt.show()
